post_text:
Thank you all for your patience and understanding this year. I know there have been many changes in the classroom, athletics, and many other areas at the school. Waskom is such a great place. Everyone loves the community, the students, and the staff. We all put students first to make sure they have a great year. It is about them. We know it hasn’t been perfect and we will continue working to make it better each day. I would challenge you to post something uplifting for our school. Our staff and students would love to hear something positive that you have experienced. A HUGE thank you to parents and the community. We are WILDCAT STRONG!

My positive experience has been the kindness you have shown WISD during difficult times. Kindness helps everyone resolve concerns. Thank you.

post_text: I know there are lots of questions about starting back to school. Please know that we are planning and will be ready. The Texas Education Agency finally released all of the information for back to school plans yesterday. I am going to finalize those with the administrative teams by next week. We will send out all of the information once it is finalized. I didn’t want a lot of misinformation floating around so I have waited until the Texas Education Agency released it first. I know you are all as curious as we were about what will be expected. Once the information is released, I will be available to discuss any concerns or questions you may have about the start of school. Thank you for your patience, support, and understanding as we work through what is best for our staff and students while meeting the mandates from the Texas Education Agency. Wildcat Strong!

Once we receive that guidance, we will begin to develop plans in regards to a future graduation ceremony for the Class of 2020. At this time, instruction will continue as it has over the last few weeks until May 22nd which is the last day of school. It is imperative that students complete their work for course credit and for promotion/retention purposes.

#COVID19 lives on droplets in the lungs of people with the virus, even if they don’t have symptoms. When infected people breathe, the virus enters the air. If you can’t #StayHome, wear a mask/scarf/bandana, stay 6 feet apart, and wash your hands. #DontGoViral

Waskom Family:

I wanted to let you know we are going to stop the meal service from April 6 - 17. That includes delivery to the houses and pick up at the school. Mr. Griffin is not able to get the food and supplies needed to sustain service. We are going to continue trying to get supplies and food in the coming weeks. We will let you know when we are able to begin the meal service again. Friday, April 3rd, Mr. Joe will give out the remainder of the food we do have at WISD.

Thank you for your understanding.

Good Evening Wildcats,

Waskom ISD has decided to close indefinitely at this time. We hope to reopen soon. We miss our students terribly. We are going to adhere to the Harrison County stay-at-home order issued by Judge Chad Sims today. Thank you for understanding. We will see you soon! Please call Central Office if you have questions.

Meal service will continue as normal.

School work will continue. More information on this coming toward the end of the week. The original packets are good through April 3rd.

Benefit Fundraiser for Alex Prather:
Alex Prather is an employee of Waskom ISD. He works in the Maintenance Department and coaches softball Funds will be used for medical and doctors bills. Mr. Prather is currently on dialysis while waiting on a kidney transplant. Donations by check or cash can be delivered to the Waskom ISD Central Administrative Office. Donations will be deposited directly into Mr. Prather's checking account. Donation receipts will be available for tax purposes. Any questions about this fundraiser can be directed to Jimmy E. Cox - Waskom ISD Superintendent. Alex Prather graciously appreciates any donations to this fundraiser.

shared_text:
Waskom Chamber of Commerce added 62 new photos to the album: Waskom Chamber of Commerce Banquet — with Jack Dillard and 4 others.
April 5, 2019 at 1:22 PM ·

Celebrating 125 Years as a community, April 1st, 2019.
The Waskom Chamber of Commerce hosted their second annual Chamber Banquet with much to celebrate over the years. Key note speaker Jack Dillard, Senior, charged his friends and Waskom neighbors to remember faith, family, & those who have come along beside them in life. A supporter of the agri-business community, local columnist and radio personality, Mr. Dillard (fondly referred to by many as "Daddy Jack") was also awarded Waskom's Citizen of the Year for 2019. Leaving those present with his gratitude and a few more unforgettable stories, Mr. Dillard challenged the Waskom membership to embrace all things Harrison County...to keep growing, and to remember their humble beginnings. Congratulations to Jack Dillard, Senior on a wonderful legacy in the making.

CDE results from Weatherford 3/27

Entomology- 6th with CJ Stevens placin 5th, Alex Hicks 18, and Gavin Finley 25th.

Horse - 21 /69 lead by Kaitlyn Woodman. Other team members were Cody Moseley, Kara Moore & Riley Otwell.

Floriculture - 29th lead again by Lindsey Garrison. Rest of team composed of Tatum McFarland, Cara Bailey & Hannah Hornaday.

Poultry - 11/35 posting their highest team score of the year so far. Top scores were Ellen Nunner and Kaleigh Garrison, along with Alaina Dyson, Taylor Culpepper, chase Kent and Preston Speight.

Livestock - 43rd lead by Ridge Riley and Chase Riley with Cody Hess, Jaden Edmundson, John Hight & Alex Jones.

Vet Science high score was Pepper White with Karlee Waltrip, Kennedy Willett, Uzi Puente, Jaiden Jones & Cayman Keeling.

All teams will compete in the Area FFA contest to qualify for state on April 16 except horse which competes Monday. Good Luck to all of our teams and students!

Hallsville FFA is with Kaitlyn Woodman.
March 18, 2019 at 10:39 AM ·

Harrison County Farm City Week off to a great start for the Hallsville FFA! This morning Ms. Jaden Elliot and Jr member Ms. Avery Hunt competed in the “Voice of Agriculture” speech contest. Avery placed 2nd in the junior division!

Also, Charleston Smith was on hand to participate in a live round table discussion with other FFA members from the county as well as members of the Harrison County Agribusiness Association on 103.9FM KMHT radio Farm Facts show with Mr. James Duncan!

Way to represent you guys! Good luck to everyone as we continue with the week’s events! Hope to see many of you there at tonight’s kick off supper and scholarship presentation at 6pm at the city arena!!!

post_text: “In politics as in philosophy, my tenets are few and simple. The leading one of which, and indeed that which embraces most others, is to be honest and just ourselves and to exact it from others, meddling as little as possible in their affairs where our own are not involved. If this maxim was generally adopted, wars would cease and our swords would soon be converted into reap hooks and our harvests be more peaceful, abundant, and happy.” George Washington

As my superintendent said, "That is the first time this has happened in Waskom since Jesus", and that speaks to the character and drive exhibited by these exceptional students.
